<h2>The crux Command</h2>
<p>
	This page is just a list of the various <code>crux</code> sub-commands and what they do.
</p>
<dl>
	
	<dt>crux init [directory]</dt>
	<dd>
		<p>
			Create a new Crux project. If a directory is given, create the project there, otherwise, create the
			project in the current working directory.
		</p>
	</dd>
	
	<dt>crux start [--quiet]</dt>
	<dd>
		<p>
			Start the project. If the <kbd>--quiet</kbd> option is given, no output will be sent to the console.
		</p>
	</dd>
	
	<dt>crux migrate create [name]</dt>
	<dd>
		<p>
			Creates a new migration, optionally with a descriptive name.
		</p>
	</dd>
	
	<dt>crux migrate [up|down] [&lt;to>]</dt>
	<dd>
		<p>
			Runs migrations in the given direction. If a <code>&lt;to></code> value is given, migrations up to and
			including the one listed will be run. If no direction is given, it will default to migrating up through
			all migrations.
		</p>
	</dd>
	
	<dt>crux npm [...]</dt>
	<dd>
		<p>
			Runs npm commands on the given project.
		</p>
	</dd>
	
	<dt>crux patch [--quiet] &lt;commit-ish></dt>
	<dd>
		<p>
			Patches the current project by merging in a commit from the online repository. <em>(Note, this command
			relies on having git installed on your system.)</em> This should not be seen as a way of updating an
			old project to a newer version of crux; This command is offered mainly for the purpose of pulling in
			necessary bug fixes and the like.
		</p>
	</dd>
	
</dl>
